ent rebellion and post-university communist agitation, the personal high point of the 1848 revolutions, and his later years of exile, political frustration, and intellectual effort. Critical yet sympathetic, Berlin's account illuminates a life without reproducing a legend. New features of this thoroughly revised edition include references for Berlin's "ations and allusions, Terrell Carver's assessment of the distinctiveness of Berlin's book, and a revised guide to further reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCommunistsvBiography. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aCarver, Terrell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarver, Terrell.1 aHardy, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatthews, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, Alan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400848119zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400848119423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400848119.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK